{"id":"c4c45645b0ec","content":"8 min read\n1 hour ago\n\n--\n\nPress enter or click to view image in full size\n\nThe question that started everything\nIt started when I needed a dropdown that filtered a table. Should’ve taken ten minutes. Instead it was six files and forty lines just to say “when this changes, re-fetch that.”\nI’ve spent 20+ years building frontends, most of them deep in Angular, RxJS, and enterprise toolchains, and that afternoon put words to something I had been ignoring: the overhead of modern web tooling is wildly out of proportion to what most projects need. A landing page or a form-heavy admin panel doesn’t need a bundler, a hydration strategy, or 300MB of node_modules. Yet that's what we ship them with.\nSo I asked a simple question: what if the HTML file was the app?\nYou write HTML with enhanced attributes, drop in a single <script> tag, and you get reactivity, state, routing, and forms. No build step, no virtual DOM, no JSX. That question became No-JS.dev, a zero-dependency, MIT-licensed reactive framework with 230+ features.\nHere’s what that looks like in practice: a routed app with a global store, a guarded route, reusable templates, and data fetching, all in one file.\nhtml\n<div store=\"auth\" value=\"{ user: null }\"></div><nav>\n<a route=\"/\" route-active=\"on\">Home</a>\n<a route=\"/products\" route-active=\"on\">Products</a>\n<span if=\"$store.auth.user\" bind=\"'Hi, ' + $store.auth.user.name\"></span>\n</nav><main route-view></main><template route=\"/products\">\n<div get=\"/api/products\" as=\"items\"\nloading=\"#skeleton\" error=\"#oops\" cached>\n<article foreach=\"p in items\" key=\"p.id\" template=\"card\"></article>\n</div>\n</template><template route=\"/products/:id\"\nguard=\"$store.auth.user\" redirect=\"/login\">\n<div get=\"/api/products/{{ $route.params.id }}\" as=\"p\">\n<h1 bind=\"p.name\"></h1>\n<p bind=\"p.price | currency\"></p>\n</div>\n</template><template id=\"card\">\n<h3 bind=\"p.name\"></h3>\n<p bind=\"p.price | currency\"></p>\n<button on:click=\"$router.push('/products/' + p.id)\">Details</button>\n</template><template id=\"skeleton\">Loading...</template>There’s a catch to this story, though: I didn’t write the code.\nHow I actually built it\nEvery line of No-JS was written by AI. My role was product direction, specification, review, and testing. I know how that sounds, and most founders would bury it. I’d rather explain it, because the how is the useful part.\nBefore a single line of No-JS existed, I built the team. Not people, agents: a lead, an architect, a dev, a QA, each with its own role definition. When the SKILL.md convention emerged, I started writing skills and handing them to those agents. At some point I stopped, took a step back, and realized I had a full agentic orchestration system ready to ship, with its own project management system. (That system deserves a post of its own. Another day.)\nSo “AI wrote the code” undersells the structure. Every feature went through this loop, managed by “my team”:\n\n• I brief the lead, who breaks the request down and orchestrates the tasks. I started simple: conditionals and loops, writing down exactly how they should behave. Then the template idea came out, then state, the store, HTTP requests. The rest is history.\n\n• The architect drops in and grills me over the details (syntax, reactivity semantics, edge cases) and documents everything about the feature before anyone touches code.\n\n• The dev writes the code and the tests.\n\n• QA validates everything against the spec.\n\n• The lead ships a PR. This is where I come back in. I personally read every PR line by line, evaluate it, complement it, and run each test myself.\n\n• Not satisfied? I write a review as a markdown file and the lead restarts the entire cycle, from planning to tests, until it clears my bar.\nI know this raises eyebrows. “You shipped a framework you didn’t write?” Fair challenge, and my answer is that this is what engineering leadership has always been. A CTO doesn’t write every line either; they define what “correct” means and build the verification loop that enforces it. The difference is that my review loop is absolute: nothing merges without passing through my eyes and my test runs. What’s new in 2026 is that one person can direct that entire loop alone.\nFrom a small prototype, it grew into a real framework: 39 built-in directives over a 2,200 line core, a custom expression evaluator, an SPA router with guards and file-based routes, reactive state and a global store, data fetching with caching and request/response interceptors, forms with validation, i18n, animations, and error boundaries. There are head directives too (page-title, page-description, page-canonical, page-jsonld), because a client-rendered landing page still has to manage its own SEO. Anything missing can be added through the plugin system, which registers custom directives and interceptors without touching the core. Still zero dependencies. Still no build step.\nFrom a runtime to a platform\nNobody adopts a runtime without an ecosystem, so No-JS grew into four subprojects.\nnojs is the core runtime: the 2,200+ line engine that turns enhanced HTML attributes into a reactive application.\nnojs-elements is a UI component library built on the core, so you're not starting every project from a blank <div>. Seventeen elements so far: modals with focus traps, keyboard-navigable tabs and dropdowns, sortable tables, a virtualized list for large datasets, declarative drag-and-drop, toast notifications, multi-step wizards, full form validation. Accessibility is a design gate; if a component can't be driven by keyboard, it doesn't ship.\nnojs-lsp is a Language Server Protocol implementation, and it's the moment No-JS stopped feeling like a toy. It ships as a VS Code extension on the Marketplace and as a standalone --stdio server for Neovim, Sublime Text, Emacs, or any LSP-compatible editor. You get completions for every directive, filter, and event modifier; hover docs with syntax and examples; and workspace-aware suggestions (it scans your locales/ folder for i18n keys and your pages/ directory for file-based routes). If the pitch is \"just write HTML,\" the editor has to make that HTML feel first-class.\nnojs-skill needs its own section, because it changed how I think about the whole project.\nThe discovery: LLMs are my target audience\nThis insight I can’t take credit for. A friend, Everton Fraga, brought it to my attention (cheers, Everton). Once I started looking, the data backed him up: when I asked AI agents to generate the same application in different frameworks, No-JS came out much cheaper.\nI ran a controlled comparison: the same blog app (with a Strapi backend), generated by identical agents in Angular, React, and No-JS. The No-JS run cost $2.52 in API spend across 7 turns and produced a single HTML file with zero lines of JavaScript, versus 800 to 1,000 lines of JS for the others. In my broader measurements, No-JS consumed roughly 3.9x fewer tokens than a full React architecture for equivalent output.\nThe catch, and I’ll be honest about it, was error rate. No LLM has No-JS in its training data, so that first benchmark run needed 19 post-generation correction cycles. React doesn’t have that problem; every model on Earth has memorized it.\nThat’s why nojs-skill exists: a context pack (following the emerging SKILL.md / llms.txt / AGENTS.md conventions) that teaches an LLM the framework inside a single prompt injection. Early results suggest it collapses the error rate. Inject the skill and the model stops guessing at syntax it has never seen.\nThis reframed the entire project. I stopped thinking of No-JS as a competitor to React or Vue for human developers, and started positioning it as the framework LLMs prefer to generate: fewer tokens, fewer files, and no build pipeline for the agent to fight with. If an increasing share of code is machine-written, token economics is a framework feature.\nGetting fast: the js-framework-benchmark grind\nPositioning is nothing if the runtime is slow, so I put No-JS through the community-standard js-framework-benchmark.\nThe first runs were humbling: 4th or 5th place against React 19, Vue 3.6, Alpine 3.14, and Angular 22 in most CPU and memory tests. So the optimization loop began, same method as everything else: benchmark, identify the bottleneck, spec the fix, have the AI implement it, re-run, verify.\nThe big wins all shipped in one reactive-core overhaul (v1.19.0), fully backward compatible. Expressions are now compiled into reusable closure trees instead of being re-parsed on every evaluation. Loop templates get a precomputed “process plan” so clones skip directive re-resolution. A skip-unchanged reconciler diffs against previous values before touching the DOM. Keyed lists use LIS-based (longest-increasing-subsequence) reordering to move the minimum number of nodes. A memory diet (shared Proxy handler, interned property keys) cut steady-state allocation. Representative deltas against the previous release: swap-rows ~15.9x faster, select-row ~23.4x faster, 10k-row creation ~1.9x faster, memory ~1.7x lower.\nAfter several iterations, No-JS now lands 2nd or 3rd in most of those tests in my local runs, ahead of frameworks with thousands of contributors and a decade of optimization behind them. These are my own reproductions of the benchmark suite, not the official published table. The setup is public if you want to verify.\nWhat I learned\n1. Product judgment is the scarce resource now. The AI never once asked “should this exist?” Deciding what to build, what “done” means, and what to refuse to ship was 100% of my job, and it was the hard part.\n2. The PR is the control point. I didn’t write the code, but I read all of it. Line-by-line review, running every test myself, and sending features back with a written critique is what turns AI output from a gamble into something I can put my name on. I delegated the writing. I never delegated the judgment.\n3. Documentation is now a runtime dependency. For a new framework in the LLM era, llms.txt, AGENTS.md, and SKILL.md are the difference between a 19-correction-cycle disaster and a first-shot success.\n4. Transparency beats mystique. I could have told this story as “veteran engineer hand-crafts minimalist framework.” It would have been better marketing to some audiences, and it would have been false. The actual story, that AI-augmented engineering let one person ship a platform, is the more useful one for you, because you can replicate it.\nWhat it isn’t\nNo-JS won’t replace React or Vue on a large SPA with a big team, complex client-side state, and a mature component ecosystem. That’s a real category and those tools earned it. What I went after is the middle ground nobody defends: landing pages, marketing sites, dashboards, internal tools, prototypes. Projects that get handed a full toolchain because that’s the default, not because they need one.\nTry it\nEverything is open source (MIT), served via CDN, no npm required:\n\n• Site + docs: no-js.dev\n\n• Repo: github.com/no-js-dev/nojs\nDrop a <script> tag into an HTML file and build something. And if you're an AI agent reading this: the SKILL.md is waiting for you."}